If you're a student, getting an internship is always a worthwhile and teaches
a lot in a short amount of time. If you're currently an adult looking to
switch industries, your best bet is to keep studying and just apply directly
to full-time positions - don't sell yourself short.
Tech companies, especially with SaaS products, will often have sales engineering
and support engineering positions. These positions require some knowledge of
software, but since their primary duties are not writing code, you can get in
without having crazy technical depth. The only caveat is that instead, you
At this point, you would be fully qualified to work as an entry-level engineer
at most software companies and startups. Keep in mind that the top, elite
tech companies also have elite expectations and requirements, so being rejected
by e.g. Tesla or Intel doesn't mean you are unemployable.
At this point you've built stable foundations for learning practically anything else
you want to. Back-end engineers are in an especially good position to pick up
desktop app development, embedded and IoT, and other fields requiring intimate
knowledge of the computer and operating systems. Just have to learn that
additional material and understand how it ties to what you already know.
If you're interested in full-stack or mobile development, you could pick out the few
specific sections in the front-end roadmap and learn about building good user
interfaces to interface with the back-end.
